@naoya_hida_co.official is having a remarkable year. Following its annual release of painstakingly handmade watches and a surprise hand-engraved collaboration with The Armoury, the Japanese independent watchmaker has now partnered with @zenithwatches for the debut of the Swiss brand's new "double signed" collection. Reviving a historic watchmaking tradition of manufacturers joining forces and sharing expertise, Zenith selected Naoya Hida as the first collaborator for the long-term initiative, centered around the legendary Calibre 135 movement from 1949.⁠
⁠
The result is a new interpretation of Zenith's G.F.J. collection, featuring hand-engraved markings by master engraver Keisuke Kan, filled with blue Japanese Urushi lacquer, alongside straps crafted from traditional Japanese materials including Himeji Kurozan leather, Kyoto Wagyu leather, and Kaihara denim. Limited to just 10 numbered pieces and priced at $75,000, the release may be one of Naoya Hida & Co.'s largest collaborative offerings to date, though demand is unlikely to be any easier to satisfy.⁠

@barbour and @adametrope have teamed up on a refined take of the brand's signature TRANSPORT CROSSBODY BAG. The collaboration updates the classic design with a more solid, minimalist look, unifying the straps, zippers, and snap buttons in matte black, while introducing ADAM ET ROPÉ-exclusive tonal logo embroidery and a house tartan lining beneath the flap.⁠
⁠
Available in black and khaki, the bag also comes with a Barbour logo pin as a special detail. The collaboration will be released at all ADAM ET ROPÉ stores and through the retailer's online shop.⁠

@olaoluslawn is stepping into the world of travel design with Slimowa, his own take on the classic suitcase. ⁠
⁠
Reworking the familiar luggage silhouette through his signature artistic lens, the project turns travel gear into collectible objects. According to Slawn's latest Instagram post, the project is scheduled to drop sometime this month.

@jilsander just dropped a new ready-to-wear collection, with several pieces featuring a new "JIL" motif. By doubling down on Sander's first name, the brand appears to be laying the groundwork for a new logo era.⁠
⁠
How do you feel about it?⁠

